<DIV1 TYPE="title page">
<PB REF="024062_0002_0FC2FD5AB75B2480">
<P>THE NATURE and NECESSITY OF AN INTERNAL CALL TO PREACH THE Everla&s;ting Go&s;pel; With Marks to di&s;tingui&s;h the Mini&s;ters of Chri&s;t from all Deceivers.</P>
<P>By ISAAC BACKUS, PASTOR OF A CHURCH IN MIDDLEBOROUGH.</P>
<Q><P>How &s;hall they preach, except they be &s;ent?</P>
<BIBL><HI>Rom. x. 15.</HI></BIBL></Q>
<P>THE SECOND EDITION, IMPROVED.</P>
<P>BOSTON: Printed and &s;old by SAMUEL HALL, in Cornhill. MDCCCXII.</P>
</DIV1>
<DIV1 TYPE="preface">
<PB REF="024062_0003_0FC2FD5BC9FE3E28">
<HEAD>THE PREFACE.</HEAD>
<P>AS the mini&s;try of the go&s;pel is a chief means of the &s;alvation of mankind, it is of great importance for all to have right ideas about the call and characters of the mini&s;ters of Chri&s;t. Yet mi&s;takes about the&s;e things are exceeding com|mon in the world. And though men generally complain of the&s;e evils, yet how few make the holy &s;criptures their only rule to guard again&s;t them? Many exclaim again&s;t old <HI>traditious,</HI> who are far from being clear of them them&s;elves; and <HI>oppo|&s;ition of &s;cience, fal&s;ely &s;o called,</HI> hath filled the world with <HI>perver&s;e di&s;putings.</HI> And we have abundant evidence, that <HI>the love of money is the root of all evil.</HI> 1 Tim. vi. 5, 10, 20. But as per&s;ecution hath not the &s;word of the magi&s;trate in America to enforce it, <HI>oppo&s;ition of knowledge</HI> cannot be &s;o fierce here, as in other countries.</P>
<P>When the en&s;uing di&s;cour&s;e was fir&s;t publi&s;hed, in the year 1754, great violence was exerci&s;ed again&s;t all mini&s;ters who were not educated for that work, and &s;upported by worldly power. And a|mong the multitude of publications &s;ince, I have never &s;een one upon the nature and nece&s;&s;ity of an internal call from God to preach his go&s;pel. And as this di&s;cour&s;e hath lately been frequently in|quired
<PB N="vi" REF="024062_0004_0FC2FD5D81A77258">after, I have thought proper to revi&s;e it, and &s;end it again into the world. For God &s;ays, <HI>If any man have not the Spirit of Chri&s;t, he is none of his.</HI> And if this be e&s;&s;ential to the character of a Chri&s;|tian, how much more for a mini&s;ter of Chri&s;t? And he &s;ays, <HI>Ye &s;hall know them by their fruits.</HI> Therefore an attempt is here al&s;o made to explain tho&s;e fruits, as they are plainly de&s;cribed in the holy &s;criptures. And each per&s;on has an equal right to judge for him&s;elf about &s;oul-guides, as he can an&s;wer it to God, who will finally reward every man according to his works: when no deceitful arts can avail with any teacher or hearer. And deceit and cruelty, under religious pretences, hath brought forth the infidelity and contempt of all vital and practical religion, which &s;o much pre|vails in our day. Men have been very careful in civil governments, to attribute all the mi&s;chiefs therein to inferior officers, or to the people, and not to the HEAD of the government; but in religi|ous matters, all the hypocri&s;ies and villanies that have appeared among tho&s;e who have profe&s;&s;ed to believe the Chri&s;tian religion, have been turned again&s;t the authority of Chri&s;t in his church. But the time is nigh, when the deaf &s;hall hear the words of God's book, and the eyes of the blind &s;hall &s;ee out of ob&s;curity, and out of darkne&s;s; the meek al&s;o &s;hall increa&s;e their joy in the Lord, and the poor among men &s;hall rejoice in the holy One of I&s;rael.</P>
